# Dijkstra's Algorithm

## The Conceptual Metaphor

Imagine you're lost in a city, and you want the *cheapest* route home — not the fewest turns, but the least total cost (tolls, fuel, time).

You carry a **running tab** for every destination. You start knowing only your own cost: zero. Everything else? Assume infinity — you haven't visited yet.

The strategy is elegant:

> *Always visit the unvisited place you can currently reach most cheaply. From there, see if you can offer cheaper routes to its neighbors. Update their tabs if so. Repeat.*

This **greedy guarantee** works because once you commit to the cheapest unvisited node, no future path can improve it — all costs are non-negative, so detours only add expense.

**Key insight:** You're not exploring blindly. You're *crystallizing certainty* outward from the source, like ice forming on a lake — the nearest water freezes first.

---

## Three Core Structures

| Structure | Role |
|---|---|
| **Distance map** | Your running tab — best known cost to each node |
| **Priority queue** | What to visit next — always the cheapest candidate |
| **Previous map** | Breadcrumbs — reconstruct the actual path later |

---

## TypeScript Implementation

