# Dijkstra's Algorithm

## The Conceptual Vision

Imagine you're a **ripple spreading across a pond**. You start at one stone (your source node) and expand outward — but the pond's surface is uneven. Some paths are shallow and fast, others deep and slow.

Dijkstra's insight: *always expand the ripple along the cheapest frontier first.* You never revisit a settled shore, because any future path to it would be longer — you already found the optimal one.

Three essential characters in this story:
- 🏝️ **Settled** — nodes with a *permanently known* shortest distance
- 🌊 **Frontier** — nodes *discovered but not yet settled* (the priority queue)
- 🌑 **Unknown** — nodes not yet touched by any ripple

The algorithm works because it greedily trusts: *"The cheapest unsettled node cannot possibly be improved later — all future paths cost at least as much."*

> ⚠️ This trust breaks with **negative edge weights** — which is why Dijkstra requires non-negative costs.

---

## The Mechanics

```
1. Assign distance 0 to source, ∞ to all others
2. Push source onto a min-priority queue
3. While the queue isn't empty:
   a. Pop the node with the smallest known distance (u)
   b. If already settled, skip it
   c. Mark u as settled
   d. For each neighbor v of u:
      - relaxedDist = dist[u] + weight(u→v)
      - If relaxedDist < dist[v]: update dist[v], push v onto queue
4. Return the distances (and optionally the path)
```

The key operation is **edge relaxation** — asking *"Does going through u give v a better deal?"*

---

## TypeScript Implementation

```typescript
// ─── Types ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

type NodeId = string | number;

interface Edge {
  to: NodeId;
  weight: number;
}

interface Graph {
  [node: NodeId]: Edge[];
}

interface DijkstraResult {
  distances: Map<NodeId, number>;
  previous: Map<NodeId, NodeId | null>;
  getPath: (target: NodeId) => NodeId[];
}

// ─── Min Priority Queue ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// A proper min-heap so we don't pay O(n) per extraction

class MinPriorityQueue {
  private heap: [number, NodeId][] = []; // [priority, value]

  get size() {
    return this.heap.length;
  }

  enqueue(value: NodeId, priority: number): void {
    this.heap.push([priority, value]);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
  }

  dequeue(): { value: NodeId; priority: number } | null {
    if (this.heap.length === 0) return null;

    const [priority, value] = this.heap[0];
    const last = this.heap.pop()!;

    if (this.heap.length > 0) {
      this.heap[0] = last;
      this.sinkDown(0);
    }

    return { value, priority };
  }

  private bubbleUp(i: number): void {
    while (i > 0) {
      const parent = Math.floor((i - 1) / 2);
      if (this.heap[parent][0] <= this.heap[i][0]) break;
      [this.heap[parent], this.heap[i]] = [this.heap[i], this.heap[parent]];
      i = parent;
    }
  }

  private sinkDown(i: number): void {
    const n = this.heap.length;
    while (true) {
      let smallest = i;
      const left = 2 * i + 1;
      const right = 2 * i + 2;

      if (left < n && this.heap[left][0] < this.heap[smallest][0])
        smallest = left;
      if (right < n && this.heap[right][0] < this.heap[smallest][0])
        smallest = right;

      if (smallest === i) break;

      [this.heap[smallest], this.heap[i]] = [this.heap[i], this.heap[smallest]];
      i = smallest;
    }
  }
}

// ─── Dijkstra's Algorithm ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

function dijkstra(graph: Graph, source: NodeId): DijkstraResult {
  const distances = new Map<NodeId, number>();
  const previous = new Map<NodeId, NodeId | null>();
  const settled = new Set<NodeId>();
  const pq = new MinPriorityQueue();

  // Initialize all nodes as infinitely far away
  for (const node of Object.keys(graph)) {
    distances.set(node, Infinity);
    previous.set(node, null);
  }

  // The source costs nothing to reach
  distances.set(source, 0);
  pq.enqueue(source, 0);

  while (pq.size > 0) {
    const { value: current } = pq.dequeue()!;

    // A node may be enqueued multiple times with stale distances — skip it
    if (settled.has(current)) continue;
    settled.add(current);

    const neighbors = graph[current] ?? [];

    for (const { to, weight } of neighbors) {
      if (settled.has(to)) continue;

      // ✨ The heart of the algorithm: edge relaxation
      const relaxedDist = distances.get(current)! + weight;

      if (relaxedDist < (distances.get(to) ?? Infinity)) {
        distances.set(to, relaxedDist);
        previous.set(to, current);
        pq.enqueue(to, relaxedDist); // Enqueue with improved distance
      }
    }
  }

  // Reconstruct path by walking the "breadcrumb trail" backwards
  function getPath(target: NodeId): NodeId[] {
    const path: NodeId[] = [];
    let current: NodeId | null = target;

    while (current !== null) {
      path.unshift(current);
      current = previous.get(current) ?? null;
    }

    // If path doesn't start at source, target is unreachable
    return path[0] === source ? path : [];
  }

  return { distances, previous, getPath };
}

